.TH NET-MGR 7 "2026-04-29" "net-mgr" "net-mgr"
.SH NAME
net-mgr \- network observation broker and tools overview
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B net-mgr
is a Perl daemon plus a set of CLI tools that maintain a MySQL/MariaDB-backed
inventory of every device on the local network: machines, interfaces, IP
addresses, listening ports, WiFi access points, client associations, and DHCP
leases. The daemon is the only process that writes to the database. Producers
push observations to it over a line-based TCP protocol; consumers subscribe
to live updates over the same socket.
.SH ARCHITECTURE
Three roles:
.IP \(bu 2
.B Daemon \fR(\fBnet-mgr\fR(8), \fBnet-dns\fR(8), \fBnet-mgr-relay\fR(8)) \(em
listens on 127.0.0.1:7531, owns the DB, dispatches OBSERVE messages, fires
events on transitions.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Producers \fR(\fBnet-discover\fR(1), \fBnet-poll-ap\fR(1),
\fBnet-import-dhcp\fR(1), \fBnet-ping\fR(1)) \(em scan or poll the network
and push observations.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Consumers \fR(\fBnet-scan\fR(1), \fBnet-show\fR(1), \fBnet-report\fR(1),
\fBnet-watch\fR(1), \fBnet-roam\fR(1)) \(em snapshot tables or stream events
without writing.
.SH POPULATING A FRESH DB
After
.BR net-mgr-setup (8)
creates the database, it's empty until producers start pushing
observations. To get an initial inventory:
.PP
.nf
.RS 4
# 1. seed from the hand-curated reservations
sudo net-import-dhcp

# 2. find live hosts (nmap sweep + fping + SSH fingerprint)
sudo net-discover --discover
sudo net-discover --presence
sudo net-discover --fingerprint

# 3. pull associations + leases from the APs
sudo net-poll-ap --auto

# 4. (optional) seed placeholder values for net-gen-dnsmasq
sudo net-var auto
sudo net-router set 192.168.15.0/24  wndr8k1  --rank 100
sudo net-router set 192.168.223.0/24 wndr8k2-down --rank 100
.RE
.fi
.PP
For ongoing population, enable the periodic scheduler in
.IR /etc/net-mgr/config :
.PP
.nf
.RS 4
[scheduling]
presence = 90s     # fping known IPs
scan-ap  = 60s     # SSH-poll APs
discover = 24h     # full nmap sweep
.RE
.fi
.PP
The daemon fires each trigger on its interval, so the steps above
become unnecessary except to bootstrap.
.SH TYPICAL WORKFLOWS
.SS Survey the network
.nf
.RS 4
net-scan                # known hosts
net-show                # APs and SSIDs
net-report aps          # raw aps table
.RE
.fi
.SS Add a new fixed-IP host
.nf
.RS 4
net-fix --mac aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff --name printer
fix_dhcp                # regenerate dhcpd.conf
.RE
.fi
.SS Investigate a flaky connection
.nf
.RS 4
net-watch 192.168.15.42         # live RTT/loss for one IP
net-report events \\
  "type IN ('interface_online','interface_offline') AND mac = 'aa:bb:..'"
.RE
.fi
.SS Find the flakiest hosts on the network (last 7 days)
Counts \fBinterface_online\fR transitions per machine in the last week
and ranks them — the top of the list is whoever is reconnecting most.
.nf
.RS 4
net-report --columns mac,machine events \\
    "type = 'interface_online' AND ts > ago(604800)" \\
  | tail -n +3 | awk '{print $1, $2}' \\
  | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn | head
.RE
.fi
.SS Push roaming clients off weak APs
.nf
.RS 4
net-roam --list                 # who's being watched
net-roam --dry-run --verbose    # what would be kicked
net-roam                        # do it
.RE
.fi
.SH PROTOCOL VERBS
The daemon speaks a line-based protocol on its TCP socket. Verbs
clients can send:
.TP
.B HELLO source=NAME | consumer=NAME
Register the kind of client (producer or consumer) before any other
verb.
.TP
.B OBSERVE \fIk=v ...\fR
Producer pushes one observation. The daemon UPSERTs the row and
emits a stream event.
.TP
.B GONE \fIk=v ...\fR
Producer signals a known item disappeared.
.TP
.B SUBSCRIBE sub=N mode=\fIM\fR FROM \fItable\fR [WHERE \fIexpr\fR]
Consumer subscribes (snapshot, stream, or both) to a table.
.TP
.B UNSUB sub=N
Cancel a subscription early; otherwise it ends when the connection
closes.
.TP
.B TRIGGER \fIname\fR [WAIT]
Async kick of a named producer (e.g.
.IR scan-ap ", " presence ).
.TP
.B POLL \fIname\fR [\fIk=v ...\fR]
Sync RPC: server runs a whitelisted local probe and returns its
output base64-encoded. Names currently registered:
.IR fw_state ", " ssh_forwards ", " host-debug
(the last is the daemon-side equivalent of
.BR net-diag (1)
with no args, used by
.BR "net-diag --remote" ).
.TP
.B STATUS
Daemon state: started_at, listeners, client counts, schema version.
.TP
.B FORWARD slot=PORT target=IP:PORT
Install a port forward from the daemon-host's loopback:PORT to the
LAN target. Backend is iptables OUTPUT-chain DNAT (default when
running as root) or
.B socat
(non-root fallback).
.B [forward] method
in the config pins the choice.
The forward lives for the duration of this connection \(em the
daemon GCs it on disconnect. Authorisation defaults to loopback
peers (127.0.0.1) only; for off-host clients add CIDRs to
.BR "[forward] allow_peers" .
Used by
.BR net-connect (1).
.TP
.B UNFORWARD slot=PORT
Release a forward early.
.TP
.B NAT_MASQUERADE iface=NAME state=on|off [boot=1]
Toggle MASQUERADE on the nat POSTROUTING chain for the named egress
interface. Idempotent. Used to make a candidate gateway routing-
ready before flipping clients onto it. Persistent (rule outlives
this connection \(em MASQUERADE on an outbound iface doesn't expose
anything inbound, so per-connection cleanup isn't needed).
.B boot=1
also writes through to
.IR /etc/iptables/rules.v4
(via
.B netfilter-persistent
when present), so the rule survives reboot. Authorisation is the
same as for FORWARD: loopback always allowed; off-host peers gated
by
.BR "[forward] allow_peers" .
.TP
.B AUTH key_id=ID
Begin SSH-key authentication. Server replies READY with a one-shot
nonce.
.TP
.B AUTH_RESPONSE sig=base64(sshsig)
Complete authentication. Client signs the nonce with its private
key (namespace=net-mgr) using
.BR ssh-keygen (1)
.B -Y sign
and base64-encodes the armored signature. Server verifies via
.B ssh-keygen -Y verify
against
.IR /etc/net-mgr/allowed_signers
augmented with each line of
.IR /root/.ssh/authorized_keys
(converted to allowed_signers format on the fly using the comment
as the principal). On OK the connection is privileged for FORWARD,
NAT_MASQUERADE, and SET_GATEWAY regardless of source IP — superseding
the IP-based
.B [forward] allow_peers
check, which remains a fallback for unauthenticated peers.
.TP
.B BYE
Clean disconnect.
.SH WEB UI
.B net-mgr-web.cgi
is an Apache CGI that renders the machine inventory as an HTML table
with click-through badges for each open port (HTTP/HTTPS render as
<scheme>://<ip>, plus ssh/vnc/rdp/smb custom-scheme links).
A
.B Tools
link in the page header opens a small landing page of dashboard
tools \(em currently a 24-hour disconnect histogram (SVG bar chart of
.B interface_offline
events bucketed per hour).
Install with the bundled
.I /etc/apache2/conf-available/net-mgr.conf
which restricts access to 192.168/16 by default, with optional
basic-auth fallback for off-LAN access. Enable with:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
a2enmod cgid && a2enconf net-mgr && systemctl restart apache2
htpasswd -c /etc/net-mgr/htpasswd <user>   # only needed off-LAN
.fi
.RE
(Use \fBrestart\fR not \fBreload\fR the first time so cgid spawns.)
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/net-mgr/config
Daemon and tool configuration. See
.BR net-mgr (8).
.TP
.I /etc/net-mgr/dhcp.master
Hand-curated authoritative DHCP reservations. Imported via
.BR net-import-dhcp (1).
.TP
.I /var/log/net-mgr.log
Daemon log.
.TP
.I /var/cache/net-mgr/
Per-tool state caches (AP poll backoff, fingerprint results).
